<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-strict.dtd">
<html lang="en" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
<head>
  <title>CSS Test: Margin Collapsing: blocks in inlines</title>
  <link rel="author" title="Ian Hickson" href="mailto:ian@hixie.ch"/>
  <link rel="alternate" href="http://www.hixie.ch/tests/adhoc/css/box/block/margin-collapse/036.html"/>
  <link rel="help" href="http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS21/box.html#collapsing-margins"/>
  <style type="text/css">
   td { width: 5em; }
   .a { display: block; border: solid; background: yellow; }
   .b { display: block; height: 1em; background: green; margin: 1em 0; }
   .c { display: inline; background: red; }
   .d { display: block; height: 1em; background: lime; margin: 1em 0; }
   .e { display: block; height: 1em; background: lime; margin: 1em 0 0; }

   .border { border: solid; background: red; }
   .green { border-top: solid green 1em; }
   .yellow { border-top: solid yellow 1em; }
   .lime { border-top: solid lime 1em; }
   .text { background: yellow; }
  </style>
 </head>
 <body>

  <p>The two boxes below should look identical.</p>

  <table>
   <tr>
    <td>
     <div class="a">
      <div class="b"></div>
      <div class="c"> <!-- empty inline box generates a line box here -->
       <div class="d"></div>
       <!-- anonymous block wraps the previous and next blocks into a single block so their margins collapse here -->
       <div class="e"></div>
      <!-- the end of the empty inline box generates a line box here --> </div>
     </div>
    </td>
    <td>
     <div class="border">
      <div class="yellow"></div>
      <div class="green"></div>
      <div class="yellow"></div>
      <div class="text">&nbsp;</div>
      <div class="yellow"></div>
      <div class="lime"></div>
      <div class="yellow"></div>
      <div class="lime"></div>
      <div class="text">&nbsp;</div>
     </div>
    </td>
   </tr>
  </table>

  <p>Note: This test is based on an interpretation of the CSS
  specification. Language lawyers could probably argue that this test
  is wrong, if they wanted to, as much as they could argue it is
  correct. However, the interpretation made by this test is probably
  the most consistent and logical in my opinion.</p>

 

</body>
</html>
